#compdef divans
# ============================================================================
# divans - Dropbox's brotli-derived compressor with
#           context-modeling extensions (Rust,
#           Apache-2.0)
#
# Author : Dropbox, Inc.
# Upstream: https://github.com/dropbox/divans
# crates : divans (binary: divans)
#
# `divans` (Dropbox's variant of brotli) is Dropbox's
# research compressor that extends the Brotli format
# (RFC 7932) with additional context-modeling features:
# context maps, arithmetic-coded stride prediction,
# external literal probability hints, and a streaming
# command-IR format that decouples the LZ77 literal /
# copy / dictionary commands from their bitstream
# encoding. The result is a compressor that beats
# stock Brotli on ~5-15% of file types (text-heavy,
# strongly-context-dependent payloads) at the cost of
# slower encode + decode throughput.
#
# divans was Dropbox's 2017 research project that
# co-evolved with their work on the `dropbox/rust-
# brotli` Rust port of Google's brotli C library;
# divans depends on `dropbox/rust-brotli` for the base
# Brotli encoder + decoder + the IR generation path.
# The project is research-focused (vs production-
# focused) but the binary is usable for ad-hoc
# compression experiments.
#
# Usage:
#   divans [flags] [input.file] [output.file]
#   divans -d [flags] [input.divans] [output.file]
#
# Flags (env::args manual parsing):
#
# Mode flags:
#   -d                       - decompress (default:
#                               compress)
#   --recode                 - decompress + re-compress
#                               (round-trip test)
#
# Quality / compression:
#   -q<N>                    - quality level (1-11
#                               Brotli + 9.5 / 9.5x
#                               extended)
#   -q9.5x                   - extended-mode 9.5
#                               quality
#   -w<N> / -window=<N>      - window size (log2)
#   -lgwin<N>                - log window size
#                               (alternate form)
#
# Context modeling:
#   -cm / -contextmap        - enable context-map
#                               extension
#   -nocm / -nocontextmap    - disable context-map
#                               extension
#   -stride<N> / -s<N>       - stride prediction
#                               (literal stride
#                               distance)
#   -nostride                - disable stride
#                               prediction
#   -nobrotli                - skip the Brotli base
#                               encoder (pure divans
#                               IR mode)
#   -brotlistride            - Brotli-style stride
#   -advbrotlistride         - advanced Brotli stride
#   -expbrotlistride         - experimental Brotli
#                               stride
#
# Encoding internals:
#   -msb / -lsb              - bit-stream byte order
#                               (most/least significant
#                               bit first)
#   -utf8                    - treat literals as UTF-8
#   -bs<N>                   - bytescore parameter
#   -sign<N>                 - sign parameter
#   -bytescore<N>            - bytescore parameter
#                               (long form)
#
# Speed selection:
#   -findprior               - search for optimal
#                               prior parameters
#   -defaultprior            - use default priors
#   -findspeed               - search for optimal
#                               speed parameters
#   -p<N>                    - parallelism level
#   -benchmark<N>            - benchmark mode
#
# CRC / integrity:
#   -skipcrc / -nocrc        - skip CRC check on
#                               decode (faster, less
#                               safe)
#   -serial                  - disable parallel
#                               encoding (force
#                               serial mode)
#
# Standard:
#   -i <file>                - input file
#   -c <file>                - output file
#   --                       - end of flags
#   -h, -help, --help        - print help
#   -v, -version, --version  - print version
#
# The brotli lane is built on `brotli = "~3.1"` (declared
# verbatim at upstream Cargo.toml HEAD as a direct dep),
# the canonical Rust Brotli implementation by Dropbox -
# github.com/dropbox/rust-brotli, 800+ stars. The
# `rust-brotli` crate is a *line-by-line port* of
# Google's reference Brotli C library to safe Rust,
# done by Dropbox engineers in 2017 to compress
# customer data at scale without exposing the
# Brotli C library to Dropbox's user-data processing
# pipeline. The port maintains byte-identical output
# vs Google's reference encoder + the same window /
# quality / stride parameter semantics.
#
# Dropbox's port preserves the line-by-line C-to-Rust
# correspondence by design: the Rust source maintains
# the same function names + the same control-flow
# structure as the C source, with only the
# memory-safety + lifetime annotations added. This
# discipline lets Dropbox catch bugs by diffing the
# Rust + C codebases (when Google's C code is patched,
# the corresponding Rust patch is mechanical), and it
# makes the Rust crate the de-facto pure-Rust canonical
# for Brotli compression.
#
# divans uses dropbox/rust-brotli's IR-generation path
# (`brotli::IRBuffer` + `brotli::interface::Command`)
# to decompose input bytes into the standard Brotli
# command stream, then feeds the commands through
# divans's own context-modeled arithmetic encoder
# (the `divans::DivansCompressor`). The decompression
# path reverses this: the divans bitstream is decoded
# back to Brotli commands + Brotli's reference
# decompressor is invoked to produce the original
# bytes.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 251 :: Brotli compression (RFC 7932)
# Round 1451 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 251
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis
# (proposed):
#   Rust    : dropbox/rust-brotli          - line-by-line
#                                            safe-Rust port
#                                            of Google's
#                                            reference C
#                                            Brotli library;
#                                            de-facto Rust
#                                            Brotli crate
#                                            (depended on
#                                            by reqwest +
#                                            wasmer + nushell
#                                            + ord)
#   Go      : andybalholm/brotli           - the canonical
#                                            Go Brotli
#                                            implementation
#                                            by Andy Balholm;
#                                            depended on
#                                            by Caddy
#                                            (default
#                                            compression
#                                            since Caddy
#                                            2.x), fasthttp,
#                                            and most Go
#                                            web servers
#   TS/Node : foliojs/brotli.js            - the original
#                                            Node Brotli
#                                            library by
#                                            Devon Govett
#                                            (foliojs)
#                                            (decompression-
#                                            only; pair with
#                                            httptoolkit/
#                                            brotli-wasm or
#                                            google-canonical
#                                            iltorb for
#                                            compression)
#
# Brotli is a clean spec-bound axis - RFC 7932 (July 2016)
# defines the bitstream format byte-for-byte. The
# algorithm was developed by Google (Jyrki Alakuijala +
# Zoltan Szabadka) as the compression backend for the
# WOFF2 web-font format + Chrome's Content-Encoding:
# br HTTP support. The Google C reference implementation
# (google/brotli) is the canonical spec-author code;
# all other implementations either bind to it (Python's
# brotli, Java's brotli4j) or reimplement it in their
# host language (Rust dropbox/rust-brotli, Go
# andybalholm/brotli, Node foliojs/brotli.js).
#
# Structural commentary on the canonical libraries:
#   - dropbox/rust-brotli (Rust): line-by-line safe-
#     Rust port maintained by Dropbox engineers;
#     unusual provenance pattern (corporate port of a
#     spec-author's C reference)
#   - andybalholm/brotli (Go): single-author pure-Go
#     reimplementation by Andy Balholm; canonical Go
#     Brotli library; depended on by Caddy +
#     fasthttp + most Go web servers
#   - foliojs/brotli.js (Node): single-author pure-JS
#     decompression-only library by Devon Govett;
#     for Brotli compression in Node, projects pair
#     with httptoolkit/brotli-wasm (a Wasm binding to
#     Google's C reference) or use Node's built-in
#     `zlib.brotliCompress` (which itself binds to
#     Google's C library)
#
# Cross-language interop at the wire format level - same
# RFC 7932 Brotli bitstream decodes byte-identically
# through all canonical implementations. Test vectors
# from the original Brotli RFC + Google's test corpus
# validate cross-library byte-equivalence.
#
# Axis 251 opens with the Rust slot at the Dropbox
# line-by-line safe-Rust port of Google's reference
# Brotli implementation.
# ============================================================================

_divans() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '-d[decompress (default is compress)]' \
        '--recode[round-trip test: decompress + re-compress]' \
        '-q9.5x[extended-mode 9.5 quality]' \
        '-q-[quality level (1-11 + 9.5)]:N:' \
        '-w-[window size (log2)]:N:' \
        '-window=-[window size (alternate)]:N:' \
        '-lgwin-[log window size]:N:' \
        '-cm[enable context-map extension]' \
        '-contextmap[enable context-map extension]' \
        '-nocm[disable context-map extension]' \
        '-nocontextmap[disable context-map extension]' \
        '-s-[stride prediction (literal stride distance)]:N:' \
        '-stride-[stride prediction]:N:' \
        '-nostride[disable stride prediction]' \
        '-nobrotli[skip Brotli base encoder (pure divans IR mode)]' \
        '-brotlistride[Brotli-style stride]' \
        '-advbrotlistride[advanced Brotli stride]' \
        '-expbrotlistride[experimental Brotli stride]' \
        '-msb[most-significant-bit-first byte order]' \
        '-lsb[least-significant-bit-first byte order]' \
        '-utf8[treat literals as UTF-8]' \
        '-bs-[bytescore parameter]:N:' \
        '-sign-[sign parameter]:N:' \
        '-bytescore-[bytescore parameter (long form)]:N:' \
        '-findprior[search for optimal prior parameters]' \
        '-defaultprior[use default priors]' \
        '-findspeed[search for optimal speed parameters]' \
        '-p-[parallelism level]:N:' \
        '-benchmark-[benchmark mode]:N:' \
        '-skipcrc[skip CRC check on decode]' \
        '-nocrc[skip CRC check on decode]' \
        '-serial[disable parallel encoding (force serial mode)]' \
        '-i[input file marker]:file:_files' \
        '-c[output file marker]:file:_files' \
        '(- *)-h[print help]' \
        '(- *)-help[print help]' \
        '(- *)--help[print help]' \
        '(- *)-v[print version]' \
        '(- *)-version[print version]' \
        '(- *)--version[print version]' \
        '*:file:_files'
}

_divans "$@"
